%N A397388 A knight starts at the origin on an infinite chessboard. In each step, it makes a knight's move to the unvisited point in the upper half-plane (y >= 0) that is closest to the origin, avoiding steps that inevitably lead to a dead end at some point in the future. See comments for how ties are resolved. a(n) is the x-coordinate of the knight after the n-th step.
%C A397388 Ties are resolved by minimizing lengths of 2nd differences, 3rd differences, and so on (see A396936). If there is still a tie after comparing the n-th differences, the lexicographically largest point is chosen. This last rule seems never to come into play, except for the very first step.
%C A397388 Backtracking (discarding a candidate move because it inevitably leads to a dead end) is needed for the first time in the 2934th step, in which the step to (40,0) is discarded because all its neighbors are already visited. Instead the knight moves to (43,3). (40,0) is also the position closest to the origin of the positions that are never visited. Among the first 1000000 steps, backtracking is needed 152 times. The majority of the discarded steps are steps to boundary points (points on the x-axis).
%C A397388 The first time the 3rd differences need to be compared is at the 6943rd step. Among the first 1000000 steps, differences of order higher than 3 never need to be compared; 3rd differences are needed 6 times.
